"{\"uid\": \"independent.co.uk-sport-olympics-jason-kenny-paris-sky-brown-british-london-b2592786.html\", \"entities\": [{\"sentence\": \"Notifications can be managed in browser preferences.\", \"from\": 0, \"to\": 52, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Please refresh the page or navigate to another page on the site to be automatically logged inPlease refresh your browser to be logged in  Swipe for next article  Removed from bookmarks  I would like to be emailed about offers, events and updates from The Independent.\", \"from\": 54, \"to\": 321, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Read ourPrivacy notice  Great Britain today won their 1,000th medal across summer and winter Olympics, according to the statistician Bill Mallon.Ethan Hayter, Dan Bigham, Charlie Tanfield, Ethan Vernon and Ollie Wood reached the milestone in the velodrome with their silver medal in the men's team pursuit at theParisOlympics.Mallon is a leading historian on the history of the Olympics and a consultant statistician to the International Olympic Committee.Here is a look at some of the medal winners over the years.\", \"from\": 322, \"to\": 837, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 346, \"end\": 359, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain_at_the_Olympics\", \"score\": 0.9999999999995453, \"rank\": 6.551782753003843e-13, \"text\": \"Great Britain\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain_at_the_Olympics\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain_at_the_Olympics\"}, {\"begin\": 473, \"end\": 479, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Stanley_William_Hayter\", \"score\": 0.9999924912804052, \"rank\": 7.508722158144389e-06, \"text\": \"Hayter\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Stanley_William_Hayter\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Stanley_William_Hayter\"}, {\"begin\": 493, \"end\": 509, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Charlie_Tanfield\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Charlie Tanfield\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Charlie_Tanfield\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Charlie_Tanfield\"}, {\"begin\": 511, \"end\": 523, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ethan_Vernon\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Ethan Vernon\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ethan_Vernon\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ethan_Vernon\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The most successfulBritishOlympian by gold medals and total medals won is SirJason Kenny, who won seven gold medals and nine overall in track cycling.\", \"from\": 839, \"to\": 989, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Launceston Elliot became Britain's first Olympic champion when he won the one-handed lift in weightlifting at the 1896 Games in Athens.\", \"from\": 991, \"to\": 1126, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 991, \"end\": 1008, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Launceston_Elliot\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Launceston Elliot\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Launceston_Elliot\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Launceston_Elliot\"}, {\"begin\": 1016, \"end\": 1023, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain\", \"score\": 0.9999999989317985, \"rank\": 1.068189332703508e-09, \"text\": \"Britain\", \"types\": [\"Q23442\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain\"}, {\"begin\": 1119, \"end\": 1125, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/2004_Summer_Olympics\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 8.52076284031123e-14, \"text\": \"Athens\", \"types\": [\"Q1656682\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/2004_Summer_Olympics\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/2004_Summer_Olympics\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"On the same day, April 7, Elliot also finished second in the two-handed lift with Charles Gmelin third in the 400 metres.\", \"from\": 1127, \"to\": 1248, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1217, \"end\": 1223, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Johann_Georg_Gmelin\", \"score\": 0.9996758887366843, \"rank\": 0.0003242161997223651, \"text\": \"Gmelin\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Johann_Georg_Gmelin\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Johann_Georg_Gmelin\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The distinction of being the first woman ever to become an individual Olympic champion goes to the 29-year-old Charlotte Cooper of Ealing who won the women's singles at the 1900 Olympic Games in Paris.\", \"from\": 1250, \"to\": 1451, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1361, \"end\": 1377, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Subways\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.9894838319156035e-17, \"text\": \"Charlotte Cooper\", \"types\": [\"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\", \"Q215380\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Subways\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Subways\"}, {\"begin\": 1445, \"end\": 1450, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"score\": 0.9999999999972715, \"rank\": 2.8825700713373036e-12, \"text\": \"Paris\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Cooper defeated the French champion, Helene Prevost in straight sets and then won a second gold medal in the mixed doubles with Reggie Doherty.\", \"from\": 1452, \"to\": 1595, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1472, \"end\": 1478, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\", \"score\": 0.9660712446651613, \"rank\": 0.03399105476956977, \"text\": \"French\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/France\"}, {\"begin\": 1496, \"end\": 1503, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pr\\u00e9vost_Car\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Prevost\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pr\\u00e9vost_Car\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pr\\u00e9vost_Car\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Shooter Jerry Millner won gold in the free rifle at 1,000 yards in the 1908 Olympics inLondon, aged 61.His background in the King's Royal Rifle Corps - Lieutenant Colonel Joshua Kearney Miller, to give him his full title - no doubt set him up for success.\", \"from\": 1597, \"to\": 1852, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1611, \"end\": 1618, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Electoral_division_of_Millner\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 9.867361464243087e-16, \"text\": \"Millner\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Electoral_division_of_Millner\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Electoral_division_of_Millner\"}, {\"begin\": 1749, \"end\": 1767, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lieutenant_colonel\", \"score\": 0.9999999981218934, \"rank\": 1.8772298204860933e-09, \"text\": \"Lieutenant Colonel\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lieutenant_colonel\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lieutenant_colonel\"}, {\"begin\": 1768, \"end\": 1774, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Book_of_Joshua\", \"score\": 0.9389746811712256, \"rank\": 0.0649914423173129, \"text\": \"Joshua\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Book_of_Joshua\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Book_of_Joshua\"}, {\"begin\": 1775, \"end\": 1782, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ken_Kearney\", \"score\": 0.9999999999890861, \"rank\": 9.434974896111827e-12, \"text\": \"Kearney\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\", \"Q13415036\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ken_Kearney\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ken_Kearney\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Sky Brownbecame Great Britain's younges